Well begin by using tidyverse.

library(tidyverse)

1. What happens if you facet on a continuous variable?

Here we have a normal plot with faceting on one axis using class, a discrete variable.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_wrap(~class, nrow=2)

As you can see, it works. Lets try switching out class for a continuous variable, say cty.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_wrap(~cty, nrow=2)

This also works, but creates an odd looking plot. The data is faceted based on intervals that allow the plot to cover the whole data set.

2. What do the empty cells in plot with facet_grid(drv ~ cyl) mean? How do they relate to this plot?

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = drv, y = cyl)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

The empty cells mean that there is no data there. There are no 4 wheel drive vehicles with 5 cylinders and no read wheel drive vehicles with 4 or 5 cylinders.

3. What plots does the following code make? What does . do?

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ .)

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ cyl)

The code makes two plots comparing hwy (highway mileage per gallon) and displ is engine displacement, in liters.

The difference is that they use two different facets. The first is filtered by drv on the y axis and the second is filtered by cyl on the x axis.

The . when used as an argument of facet_grid() allows you to create a facet grid with only one facet rather than having to use facet_wrap()

4. Take the first faceted plot in this section. What are the advantages to using faceting instead of the colour aesthetic? What are the disadvantages? How might the balance change if you had a larger dataset?

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

Faceting rather than color aesthetic allows for clearer separation of data. Conversely, its more difficult to compare data points easily. With a larger data set, faceting will become more useful as you can seperate out overlapping data points that are part of different facets.

5. Read ?facet_wrap. What does nrow do? What does ncol do? What other options control the layout of the individual panels? Why doesnt facet_grid() have nrow and ncol arguments?

nrow and ncol are the number of rows and columns respectively. as.table will change tha layout of a facet to be like a table. dir changes the direction.

facet_grid() doesnt have nrow and ncol because its a grid and the number of rows and columns is automatically based on the data set and is usually used with discrete variables. Its best for when all the combinations of two discrete variables exist in the data set.

6. When using facet_grid() you should usually put the variable with more unique levels in the columns. Why?

This variable with more unique levels should be put in the column to allow greater distinction in the data.
